service_name: Calaim Community Supports - Serene Health Ipa
service_description:
Provides the following CalAIM Community Support Services:

  • Housing Transition Navigation Services - Provides help to find, apply for, and secure housing to members experiencing homelessness or at risk of experiencing homelessness.
  • Housing Deposits - Provides assistance with housing security deposits, utilities set-up fees, first and last month's rent, and first month of utilities. Members can also receive funding for medically necessary items like air conditioners, heaters, and hospital beds to ensure their new home is safe for move-in.
  • Housing Tenancy - Provides support to maintain safe and stable tenancy once housing is secured, such as coordination with landlords to address issues, assistance with the annual housing recertification process, and linkage to community resources to prevent eviction.
  • Short Term Post Hospitalization Housing - Provides short-term housing (up to six months) for members who do not have a residence, and who have high medical or mental health and substance use disorder needs so they can continue recovery. To receive this support, members must also have been discharged from an inpatient clinical setting, residential substance use disorder treatment or recovery facility, residential mental health treatment facility, correctional facility, nursing facility, or recuperative care.
  • Recuperative Care/Medical Respite - Provides short-term residential care for members with unstable housing who no longer require hospitalization, but still need to heal from an injury or illness. The residential care includes housing, meals, ongoing monitoring of the member's condition, and other services like coordination of transportation to appointments.
  • Medically Tailored Meals or Groceries - Provides deliveries of nutritious, prepared meals and healthy groceries to support the member's health needs. Members also receive vouchers for healthy food and/or nutrition education.
  • Respite Services - Provides short-term relief for member caregivers. Members may receive caregiver services in their home or in an approved facility on an hourly, daily, or nightly basis as needed.
taxonomy_terms: Medical Equipment Expense Assistance, General Household Goods Provision, Rental Deposit Assistance, Appliances, Home Delivered Meals, Transitional Housing/Shelter, Medical Respite Facilities/Beds for Homeless People, Children's In Home Respite Care, Furniture, Housing Counseling, Nutrition Education, Adult In Home Respite Care, Out of Home Respite Care, Rent Payment Assistance, Food Vouchers
application_process: Call for services

organization_description: A nonprofit organization based in San Diego that supports low-income families navigating childhood cancer and other life-threatening illnesses.
service_description: Provides free, door-to-door transportation to medical appointments across San Diego, Orange, and Imperial Counties, ensuring that no child misses life-saving treatment due to lack of transportation. ENF also offers one-on-one support at its Family Resource Center inside Rady Children's Hospital-soon expanding to CHOC in Orange County-where families receive help completing applications for Medi-Cal, SSI, housing, and food assistance. Additional programs include Emilio's Healthy Snack Bags, which provide nutritious food after treatment, and Creating for Hope, which offers therapeutic arts activities for caregivers. Through these services, ENF provides compassionate, culturally responsive support to all families, removing barriers so they can focus on their child's healing.
application_process: Walk-inApplicants can expect to be contacted within 24 hours after reaching out to the Emilio Nares Foundation (ENF). During the initial contact, they will be asked questions about the child's diagnosis and date of birth, and an intake will be completed that includes the child's and parent's information to determine eligibility for services. If no one is available to answer the call right away, families can expect a callback within one business day

organization_description: Builds strong, stable, and secure military families through emergency financial assistance, housing, and recurrent family support programs.
service_description: Operation Homefront's Transitional Housing Program allows these service members to live rent free while they go through the transition process. Upon placement, Operation Homefront counselors set up a mandatory schedule that these service members, veterans and their families must follow. They are required to attend support groups, workshops, benefits briefings, and resume writing classes, as determined by their counselor. They also undergo one-on-one financial counseling to reduce debt and build savings. OH counselors meet with each military family every 30 days to review their financial situation, determine where they are in the transition process, review their attendance in the required workshops and classes, and determine their ability to live on their own. Once they have become self-sufficient, OH counselors help them find suitable housing in the area they intend to live on a permanent basis. Upon completion of the program, veterans and their families should have VA benefits in place, debt significantly reduced and emergency savings in place.

organization_description: The non-profit victim contact center provides toll-free, no-cost guidance and information to victims of identity compromise and misuse, scams or fraud. Services are provided to people in New Hampshire.
service_description:
The ITRC provides free help to anyone who wants to identify if they are a victim of identity theft, protect their personal information and/or prevent themselves from becoming a victim of an identity crime, or recover from identity misuse. 

The ITRCs Victim Advisors will walk all victims through what steps they need to take and are happy to serve as a resource for as long as they are needed. The ITRC does not collect sensitive personal information, only basic contact information and demographic information, if the individual is willing to share. Individuals may want to know how to protect their information if their purse/wallet/phone/tablet/ laptop/documents were stolen or if they were a victim of a data breach. 

The ITRC can help if a US-based account was opened in an individuals name, or one of their accounts has been taken over. Accounts include but are not limited to social media accounts (Facebook, Instagram, etc.), government accounts (IRS, SSA, etc.), financial accounts (bank, credit card, etc.), and utility accounts (cable, electricity, phone, etc.)
taxonomy_terms: Internet Information Resources, Identity Theft Reporting/Recovery Programs, Identity Theft Prevention

service_description:
Provides a warmline for new mothers experiencing a postpartum mood disorder such as depression or anxiety. The warmline is volunteer-run, and all volunteers are experienced moms who have recovered from a postpartum disorder. Volunteers are there to listen and provide personalized clinical referrals. May also assist with identifying alternative perinatal supports such as doulas, lactation consultants, or parent support groups in the caller's area.


If a caller is thinking about hurting herself or her baby, they can get help right away by calling 800-PPDMOMS or 800-944-4773.

service_description: Offers support and services for veterans and service members who incurred a physical or mental injury, illness, or wound, co-incident to their military service on or after September 11, 2001. Services and support are also available for family members and caregivers.Types of Support: Benefits Service: Helping veterans and their families obtain the benefits they have earned. Combat Stress Recovery Program: Help for combat stress, PTSD and TBI. Community Partners: Strategic collaboration improving veteran care across the nation. Family Support: Veteran family program and caregiver support. Independence Program: Empowering warriors to live a more independent life. International Support: Support for wounded, ill, or injured service members who are medically evacuated to Landstuhl Regional Medical Center in Germany. Peer Support: Peer support groups for veterans. Physical Health & Wellness: Helping warriors improve their health. Policy & Government Affairs: A voice for warriors in Washington, DC. Soldier Ride: Building confidence and strength through shared physical activities and bonds of service. Warrior Care Network: Healing the invisible wounds of war through PTSD treatment for veterans. Warriors to Work: Career transition and development for America's injured veterans. WWP Resource Center: Welcomes warriors and their families into WWP and serves as a connection point at every step along their individual journeys. WWP Talk: Counseling for veterans and their families.

organization_description: Statewide organization offering free telephone counseling, self-help materials, and a texting program in six languages to help you quit smoking.
service_description: Provides individuals with a choice of materials and services to quit smoking, vaping, or chew. Services include one-on-one phone counseling, supportive text messages, and free nicotine patches. Mobile apps, quitting tips through Amazon's Alexa, and a referral list of smoking cessation programs are also available.
taxonomy_terms: Smoking/Vaping Cessation, Talklines/Warmlines, Tobacco Use Education/Prevention, Outreach Programs
application_process:
To receive one-on-one counseling over the phone, please call one of the following phone numbers during program hours:
Smokers - 1-800-NO-BUTTS (1-800-662-8887)
Vape Users - 1-844-8-NO-VAPE (1-844-866-8273) 
Tobacco Chewers - 1-800-844-CHEW (1-800-844-2439)
Chinese - 1-800-838-8917
Korean - 1-800-556-5564
Spanish - 1-800-45-NO-FUME (1-800-456-6386)
Vietnamese - 1-800-778-8440

To receive texts messages that are tailored to help at critical points: 
English - Text "Quit Smoking" to 66819 or Text "Quit Vaping" to 66819 
Spanish - Texto "dejar de fumea" al 66819 or Texto "no vapear" al 66819

To receive self-help materials on quitting call 1-800-NO-BUTTS or visit https://bit.ly/3m0ny73.

To see if you qualify for free nicotine patches, call 1-800-NO-BUTTS.

To download the No Butt app, visit https://apps.apple.com/us/app/no-butts/id1235248992 or https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=edu.ucsdcsh.

To download the No Vape app, visit https://apps.apple.com/us/app/no-vape-crush-cravings/id1488178260 or https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=edu.ucsdcsh.vape&hl=en_US.

To receive tips on how to quit smoking through Amazon Alexa, enable the Stop Smoking Coach on Amazon.com at https://amzn.to/3hjoxM2.

To receive tips on how to quit vaping through Amazon Alexa, enable the Stop Vaping Coach on Amazon.com at https://amzn.to/2RhVPAx.
 
To find available smoking cessation programs by county, visit: https://www.nobutts.org/county-listing.

service_name: Identity Theft Resource Center, Id Theft Counseling
organization_description: Provides victim and consumer support as well as public education.
service_description: ID THEFT COUNSELING: Provides free help for all victims of identity and cybercrime, including identity compromise, identity theft, and identity misuse. Walks victims through what steps need to be taken and serves as a resource for as long as it takes to resolve the issue. Assistance is provided via phone, live chat, or email. In person assistance is not available currently. Identity compromise includes, but is not limited to, personal information given to a scammer, exposed in a data breach, or documents (tax, Social Security card, driver's license, passport, etc.) that were lost or stolen. Identity misuse includes, but is not limited to, personal information that was used without permission by a scammer or thief to open new accounts or take over existing accounts. Examples include filing taxes in someone's name, opening credit in someone's name, taking over a social media account, collections in someone's name for an account they didn't open, or a criminal record for crimes a person did not commit.
application_process: Call for information or visit the website. Live chat is available on the website.

organization_description: TOOTRiS believes that every child deserves the opportunity to attend high-quality Child Care. As a tech-enabled service that combines tools for parents, providers, and employers, all within a single app, we empower working parents - especially women - by delivering real time access to Child Care, enabling them to find, communicate, enroll and pay, all while completely contactless. Providers grow their program with TOOTRiS curriculums, business, and marketing automation, while employers incorporate Child Care-as-a-Benefit, increasing their productivity, attracting and retaining top talent. In response to classrooms going virtual, we have created Learning Hubs, a service that provides safe and supervised small group environments designed to give school-aged children a place to learn and thrive. As we all adapt to our "new normal," TOOTRiS gives parents peace of mind that their children, the most important people in the world, are safe and secure in high-quality care. TOOTRiS is headquartered in San Diego, California. Learn more at tootris.com.
